# Python Functions, File Handling, OS Module & Miscellaneous

## 📖 Introduction

This section covers the built-in functions, file handling methods, OS module functions, and other important concepts learned throughout the Python course.

---

# 📋 File Handling Methods

| Function / Method | Use                                                         |
| ----------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |
| `open()`          | Opens a file and returns a file object.                     |
| `close()`         | Closes an opened file and releases system resources.        |
| `read()`          | Reads the entire file or a specified number of characters.  |
| `readline()`      | Reads a single line from a file.                            |
| `readlines()`     | Reads all lines and returns them as a list.                 |
| `write()`         | Writes text to a file.                                      |
| `writelines()`    | Writes multiple lines to a file.                            |
| `seek()`          | Moves the file pointer to a specified position.             |
| `tell()`          | Returns the current position of the file pointer.           |
| `flush()`         | Forces buffered data to be written to the file immediately. |
| `truncate()`      | Resizes the file to a specified size.                       |
| `readable()`      | Checks whether the file is readable.                        |
| `writable()`      | Checks whether the file is writable.                        |
| `seekable()`      | Checks whether the file supports random access.             |
| `fileno()`        | Returns the file descriptor used by the operating system.   |
| `isatty()`        | Checks whether the file is connected to a terminal.         |
| `readinto()`      | Reads binary data directly into a writable buffer.          |
| `detach()`        | Separates the underlying binary buffer from a text stream.  |

